WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.360
Hi everybody, my name is Hannah Podzorski, and today I want to talk to you about how

00:00:10.360 --> 00:00:17.320
I adapted current tools in environmental science through R by advocating for automation.

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:21.959
And to start, I want to tell you a little bit about my colleague, let's call him John.

00:00:21.959 --> 00:00:25.040
I work with a lot of Johns.

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:29.480
John might be a biologist, a chemist, maybe a geologist.

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:33.520
He's been in his field for quite some time, and he has a lot of very important technical

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:39.880
knowledge within his field, but little to no knowledge on modern day programming languages.

00:00:39.880 --> 00:00:46.200
In addition to this, John keeps getting handed data sets that are much larger and more complex

00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:49.639
than what his current tools can handle.

00:00:49.639 --> 00:00:54.759
And on top of this, just like everybody else, he's got too many tasks and not enough time.

00:00:54.759 --> 00:00:58.660
So this is the type of scenario where I would advocate for automation.

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:02.980
My goal is to streamline the processing of data so my team has more time to apply their

00:01:02.980 --> 00:01:07.639
technical knowledge to the problem at hand.

00:01:07.639 --> 00:01:10.959
But John might be a little bit hesitant.

00:01:10.959 --> 00:01:13.720
And I understand that.

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:17.639
Because as a programmer, I would much rather spend five days automating something than

00:01:17.639 --> 00:01:20.839
just five minutes to do a simple task.

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:24.959
Because of that, not only today am I going to talk to you about how I used R to automate

00:01:24.959 --> 00:01:32.800
workflows, but also how I reduced the activation energy it took to get my team on board.

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:37.000
So in chemistry, activation energy is the energy needed to get from one side of a chemical

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.019
reaction to another.

00:01:40.019 --> 00:01:44.660
And you can reduce the activation energy by applying a catalyst.

00:01:44.660 --> 00:01:48.839
So when I want to move my team from their current workflow to an automated workflow,

00:01:48.839 --> 00:01:55.199
I can reduce the activation energy by rephrasing how I pitch automation, starting small, and

00:01:55.199 --> 00:01:58.320
being a little bit creative.

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:02.519
So let's start with the pitch, and most importantly, that word automation.

00:02:02.519 --> 00:02:07.400
It can be a little vague and field dependent, but what I mean when I say automation is the

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:12.639
streamlining of a workflow by reducing unnecessary human interactions.

00:02:12.639 --> 00:02:17.919
So my team has more time to spend on greater value tasks.

00:02:18.119 --> 00:02:21.160
Most times when I pitch automation, I don't even use the word automation.

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:25.279
I say let's streamline this workflow.

00:02:25.279 --> 00:02:28.880
So let's talk about the difference between workflow that I traditionally see, which I'm

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:34.059
going to call for the purposes of this talk reactionary workflow and automated workflow.

00:02:34.059 --> 00:02:40.000
So let's say we have four work products, A, B, C, and D. A might be our database, B might

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:46.160
be our tables full of summary stats, C is our figures, and D is the text that goes into

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:48.199
our final report.

00:02:48.199 --> 00:02:50.679
Say we have to update our database.

00:02:50.679 --> 00:02:54.399
Maybe we know that we need to update our database, like we need to go out and collect more data,

00:02:54.399 --> 00:03:01.399
or maybe we don't know and maybe someone found an error in unit conversions at the last minute.

00:03:01.399 --> 00:03:07.720
Well with this change, now we have to manually update all of the workflow downstream.

00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:13.160
In comparison, an automated workflow, if you have to make that one change to your database,

00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:18.119
you can use functions or scripts to automate the processing of that one edit and apply

00:03:18.119 --> 00:03:20.479
it to all of your work products downstream.

00:03:20.479 --> 00:03:26.080
And this is, I know, a very simple definition of what automation is and streamlining a workflow,

00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:31.320
but I like to lay it out like this because it makes the pros or benefits of using automation

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:33.160
very obvious.

00:03:33.160 --> 00:03:35.000
So number one, reproducibility.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.679
Because of those scripts or those recipes that are being completed by a computer, you

00:03:39.679 --> 00:03:42.199
know you're going to get the same thing every time.

00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:46.800
And this is important not just when you can predict you need to update something, like

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:51.119
we're going to do annual sampling events, but also when you can't predict, you're going

00:03:51.119 --> 00:03:57.639
to need to update something like when you catch an error in a simple mathematic equation.

00:03:57.639 --> 00:04:01.520
Also it can be extremely simple, and though it pains me to say this, this type of workflow

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:07.240
can be accomplished in Excel workbooks, just maybe not at the current scale we need.

00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:11.000
It saves time because you're reducing that human interaction and also reducing the amount

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:17.359
of errors, which saves my team time in quality control and quality assurance.

00:04:17.359 --> 00:04:22.160
So I found it helpful to start small with tasks that can be automated in the same amount

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:24.640
of time as the original tasks.

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:29.279
And so for me and the projects I work on, this is most likely going to be moving tables

00:04:29.279 --> 00:04:34.359
of summary statistics and figures out of Excel and into R.

00:04:34.359 --> 00:04:38.480
But most importantly, I like to try and meet my team members where they are, and that's

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:42.920
going to be by creating work products they're familiar with, and at least in my case, that's

00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:46.760
going to most likely be Microsoft Office products.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:52.399
So I'm going to talk about two packages I love for doing this, the first one being OpenXLXS.

00:04:52.399 --> 00:04:59.000
It's a package designed to edit, read, and create Excel files in R.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:05.040
So traditionally when I go to save a data frame in R, I'm going to write it as a CSV.

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:09.600
However, more recently I've tried to force myself to save more of these data frames,

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:15.040
especially the ones I know that are going to be of interest to my team, to Excel files.

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:19.799
That's because I want to help them with this transition between the reactionary workflow

00:05:19.799 --> 00:05:22.279
and the automated workflow.

00:05:22.279 --> 00:05:26.640
Because when they're working on so many projects at the same time, and they're used to all

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:33.040
their files being dynamic and constantly changing, and also all written in Excel, and you throw

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:39.839
one CSV in there, more than once have they opened that CSV in Excel, added a few tabs,

00:05:39.839 --> 00:05:42.920
highlighted a few cells, saved it, and closed out.

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:47.160
And since those edits are not supported in CSV, they just lost all that work.

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:53.700
So by me making the simple change of simply saving data frames as .XLS files, I'm helping

00:05:53.700 --> 00:05:58.839
to reduce the activation energy and get my team moving forward towards automation.

00:05:58.839 --> 00:06:03.799
Also I love OpenXLSX because it allows me to make formatted Excel tables in R, such

00:06:03.799 --> 00:06:08.299
as the one you see here, and it's great for when I have to put together hundreds of tables

00:06:08.299 --> 00:06:13.380
that I'll go into a back of a report, which I'm sure eventually one day someone might

00:06:13.380 --> 00:06:17.440
look at, maybe.

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:19.079
Also I love to use Officer.

00:06:19.079 --> 00:06:24.640
Officer allows you to manipulate Word documents and PowerPoint documents in R. I use it mostly

00:06:24.640 --> 00:06:27.920
for exporting GG plots into PowerPoint.

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:32.359
And so here's just example code doing just that, but what I want to do is I want to point

00:06:32.359 --> 00:06:36.739
out the RVG package and the function DML.

00:06:36.739 --> 00:06:41.600
So running your GG plot object through this, in our case our GG plot object is plot, through

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:47.239
this function, before you export that figure to PowerPoint, allows you to actually edit

00:06:47.239 --> 00:06:49.000
that figure in PowerPoint.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:54.480
So here's an example of a plot I created and exported to PowerPoint using the code from

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:56.119
the previous slide.

00:06:56.119 --> 00:07:04.200
It's the concentration of chloride over time, and since I used the DML function, I can move

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:10.000
around my annotations, change them, I can change the access titles and the legend, and

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.760
this is great for if my team wants to just have a little bit more control of the final

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:18.799
product or if they just don't like where the annotation is currently at or if they want

00:07:18.799 --> 00:07:24.239
to make last-minute nomenclature adjustments, this makes it great so we can still interact.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:29.559
In addition with Officer, you can use PowerPoint templates to create placeholders, and then

00:07:29.559 --> 00:07:35.359
you can add things like figure captions, figure numbers, notes, logos, so I can automate the

00:07:35.359 --> 00:07:40.480
process of creating these figures and export them from R into PowerPoint so they're ready

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:46.600
for a report.

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:51.399
So now that I've got my team a little bit on board, I've started with these smaller tasks,

00:07:51.399 --> 00:07:57.359
now I can take on bigger tasks that might require a little bit more of initial investment

00:07:57.359 --> 00:08:02.799
and delayed gratification, so I'm going to talk just about that, a specific example where

00:08:02.799 --> 00:08:08.279
my team decided to automate software developed by a regulatory agency.

00:08:08.279 --> 00:08:14.079
So that software is Pro-UCL, Pro-UCL was developed by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency

00:08:14.079 --> 00:08:20.480
or EPA, and it specializes in performing statistical analysis on left-sensor data.

00:08:20.559 --> 00:08:24.600
In environmental sciences, we have a lot of left-sensor data, whenever we're measuring

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:30.480
the concentration of some compound in water or soil or air, depending on our methods and

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:33.919
our equipment, we have something called a detection limit, and below that detection

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:38.039
limit, we don't know where that concentration will sit, it can be anywhere between zero

00:08:38.039 --> 00:08:42.400
and our detection limit, so there's a lot of uncertainty around that.

00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:47.960
So Pro-UCL takes that uncertainty into account when doing simple statistics like means and

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:53.719
standard deviations, as well as more complex statistics like distributions and upper confidence

00:08:53.719 --> 00:08:54.880
limits.

00:08:54.880 --> 00:09:01.960
So Pro-UCL is definitely, it's solving a problem for us, but it has some less than great design

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:07.080
features, one of which is it will crash if you put too much data into it, and by too

00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:11.679
much I mean about 10,000 records, which for the type of projects we're working on, which

00:09:11.679 --> 00:09:17.559
require us to analyze hundreds of compounds in a variety of environmental media, we were

00:09:17.559 --> 00:09:20.760
having to run Pro-UCL multiple times.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:24.359
And because of that, we decided we wanted to try and automate it, and we decided to

00:09:24.359 --> 00:09:33.799
try and automate it by using a mouse macro, so in our case it's called mini-mouse macro,

00:09:33.799 --> 00:09:37.880
and basically automate the clicking of the software itself.

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:46.440
So we wrote a function in R that allows us to subset that data into more manageable chunks,

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:51.919
and then you run the function, and it creates an input file for our mouse macro, and then

00:09:51.919 --> 00:09:53.440
it runs that file.

00:09:53.440 --> 00:09:56.000
So the mouse macro input is just a simple text file.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:01.479
I used some command line code to open up the mouse macro and load in the input file, and

00:10:01.479 --> 00:10:05.479
then it just clicks through the software for you.

00:10:05.479 --> 00:10:10.419
So here it's using the text string we gave it to input the location of the input file.

00:10:10.419 --> 00:10:15.840
It's clicking through all of the dropdowns we'll need, and then it's loading in the compounds

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:20.719
we want to look at, and finally, it'll save that file to the text string I gave it for

00:10:20.719 --> 00:10:23.320
the output file.

00:10:23.320 --> 00:10:28.119
And then once it senses that there's information in that file, it'll close out of Pro-UCL,

00:10:28.119 --> 00:10:29.820
and if necessary, run it again.

00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:31.919
So we'll loop this over and over and over again.

00:10:31.919 --> 00:10:33.919
And that might have seemed like a very simple process.

00:10:33.919 --> 00:10:35.200
Why would you automate it?

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:39.640
Well, that was a very small data set, and there's actually a lot of computation time

00:10:39.640 --> 00:10:42.919
that has to go into it when you're doing larger data sets.

00:10:42.919 --> 00:10:48.840
So for small projects, running Pro-UCL through the automation like this can take 15 to 30

00:10:48.840 --> 00:10:54.760
minutes, but for bigger projects, we're talking just automating like this, six to eight hours.

00:10:54.760 --> 00:10:57.479
So it's definitely saving us time that way.

00:10:57.479 --> 00:11:00.799
But writing the code to automate the clicking of my mouse through the software was actually

00:11:00.799 --> 00:11:02.320
the easy part.

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:07.340
The hard part was deciphering the output file.

00:11:07.340 --> 00:11:10.799
So here's what Pro-UCL gives you as an output file.

00:11:10.799 --> 00:11:13.159
It's a formatted Excel sheet.

00:11:13.159 --> 00:11:17.780
This is just a small subsection of the statistics it gives you and only one compound.

00:11:17.780 --> 00:11:21.679
So once again, for our sites, we're looking at hundreds of compounds, and we might even

00:11:21.679 --> 00:11:28.080
have to group our data spatially, so we'll need additional information.

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:32.080
And so before we automated, what we did was just have someone go through and copy and

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:35.520
paste the values we were really interested in.

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:37.320
And that took quite some time.

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:42.760
So instead, we automated it, and now we create tables both unformatted and formatted in Excel

00:11:42.760 --> 00:11:49.479
that my team can use for their analysis and their final report.

00:11:49.479 --> 00:11:52.960
So overall, my team thinks this went great.

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:55.640
It does exactly what we want it to do.

00:11:55.640 --> 00:12:00.280
When we first decided we wanted to automate Pro-UCL, we saw two paths we could go down,

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:06.460
one using our mouse macro, the other just recreating all the statistical tests in R,

00:12:06.460 --> 00:12:11.059
and that definitely would have been possible, but at the time, we just didn't have the resources

00:12:11.059 --> 00:12:14.140
or the time to devote to such a project.

00:12:14.140 --> 00:12:19.539
In addition, Pro-UCL is an industry standard almost at this point.

00:12:19.539 --> 00:12:23.260
It's been used for quite some time, and there's a lot of important technical knowledge built

00:12:23.260 --> 00:12:29.460
into it, so using it is a benefit, especially when we have to deal with regulators.

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:34.539
In addition, Pro-UCL is used on projects such as risk assessments, where we look at how

00:12:34.700 --> 00:12:41.940
compounds in the environment can affect different receptors, like humans and wildlife, and sometimes

00:12:41.940 --> 00:12:47.580
we have to go back and forth with regulatory agencies to define our conceptual model for

00:12:47.580 --> 00:12:52.500
a site, which means we might be adding in receptors, we might be adding in compounds,

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:57.479
we might be changing how we spatially divide up our data, and that means we very rarely

00:12:57.479 --> 00:13:02.539
have to just run Pro-UCL once, usually two or three times.

00:13:02.539 --> 00:13:06.700
So automating it definitely saved time, it saved human error, because less copying and

00:13:06.700 --> 00:13:10.940
pasting, but it's not perfect.

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:17.299
Once I'm sure, one day hopefully, EPA will update Pro-UCL, and then my code will become

00:13:17.299 --> 00:13:21.099
obsolete, but at this point, it's already paid for itself, it works, it does what we

00:13:21.099 --> 00:13:24.020
need it to do, and we're happy for that.

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:28.659
In addition, there are other things I wanted to do to help improve this function, to make

00:13:28.659 --> 00:13:34.780
it easier to use for anybody, but we just didn't have the time, so it does require some

00:13:34.780 --> 00:13:39.580
special setup, especially with the coordinates for the clicking of the mouse, you have to

00:13:39.580 --> 00:13:44.340
make sure your screen resolution is set appropriately.

00:13:44.340 --> 00:13:49.780
So final thoughts, I gave you a bunch of different hybrid approaches to automation that helped

00:13:49.780 --> 00:13:55.419
me save time and reduce human error, which ultimately is what I believe the goal of automation

00:13:55.419 --> 00:13:57.500
is and should be.

00:13:57.500 --> 00:14:02.299
So I showed some easier examples and some more advanced, so I hope you recognize that

00:14:02.299 --> 00:14:07.219
no matter what your skill set, you can benefit your team now, and maybe with just a little

00:14:07.219 --> 00:14:13.559
bit of rephrasing of your pitch, starting small and being creative, you too can help,

00:14:13.559 --> 00:14:17.820
you can reduce the activation energy needed to get your team on board, and reduce the

00:14:17.820 --> 00:14:20.580
road bumps along the way.

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:24.859
And with that, if we have, I can go ahead and answer questions.

00:14:24.859 --> 00:14:29.020
First I wanted to let everybody know at this link are my slides, as well as example code

00:14:29.020 --> 00:14:35.099
for the smaller examples, so the open XLSS and the officer, as well as links to more

00:14:35.099 --> 00:14:36.099
information.

00:14:37.099 --> 00:14:38.099
Thank you.

00:14:38.099 --> 00:14:39.099
Thank you.

00:14:39.099 --> 00:14:40.099
Thank you.

00:14:40.099 --> 00:14:40.099


